  <content>
    <title>Success Metrics Definition</title>

    <summary>Teams measure the wrong things or too many things. Common issues: vanity metrics that don't drive decisions, too many KPIs with no focus, metrics that don't connect to business outcomes, and no targets or baselines. The root cause is having no structured process for identifying what truly matters. Success metrics are quantifiable measures that indicate whether you're achieving your goals. They answer: How do we know if we're winning? This methodology guides you through identifying what truly matters via a structured process that connects business goals to the AARRR framework, sets actionable targets, and guards against vanity metrics.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Most teams either track nothing useful or track too many things. Success metrics move beyond surface-level counts to connect business value. A North Star metric guides strategy. Primary KPIs across the AARRR stages create a balanced system. Guardrails prevent Goodhart's law — where optimizing for a metric stops making it a good metric.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up KPIs for a new product, feature, or campaign before launch.</item>
        <item>Re-baselining metrics quarterly when business goals shift.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new team and aligning on a single North Star.</item>
        <item>After noticing the team optimizes for vanity numbers like signups or page views.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>During exploratory pre-PMF work — set qualitative milestones, not KPIs.</item>
        <item>For one-off experiments — use a single success criterion, not a full AARRR scaffold.</item>
        <item>When data infrastructure is missing; defining metrics without instrumentation creates aspirational dashboards.</item>
        <item>For purely creative/editorial work where the metric becomes a distorting incentive.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="metric-types">
      <p>Input vs Output Metrics. Input metrics are leading indicators — activities you control like blog posts published or outreach emails sent. Output metrics are lagging indicators — results of activities like organic traffic or customer signups. The rule is simple: Track both. Inputs predict outputs. Without leading indicators, you are reactionary. Without outputs, you don't know if activities are working.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every primary KPI must have a paired leading indicator. For example, organic traffic (output) pairs with published posts or backlinks built (inputs). Growth rate (output) pairs with trial signups or feature adoption (inputs).</statement>
        <rationale>Leading indicators allow you to course-correct before lagging metrics move. They give you signal weeks or months earlier. Without inputs, you are flying blind and can't optimize the engine.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Vanity vs Actionable Metrics. Vanity metrics look good on the surface but don't drive decisions. Total signups ever is vanity — it only goes up. Weekly active users is actionable because it correlates with retention. The test: If this metric changes, will we do something different? If the answer is no, it is vanity and wastes dashboard space.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every metric must pass the actionability test. If you cannot articulate what action you would take if the metric dropped 50%, it is vanity and should be retired.</statement>
        <rationale>Vanity metrics create false confidence. They feel like progress when they aren't. Actionable metrics drive decisions and resource allocation. Teams that track vanity metrics optimize for the wrong things and waste months.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Metric Hierarchy. Metrics organize in a tree. At the top sits one North Star metric — the single most important number. Below it: 3-5 primary KPIs, one per lifecycle stage (AARRR). Below those: secondary metrics and leading indicators that support each KPI. On the side: health metrics (guardrails) that catch unintended consequences. For example, a marketplace might have Weekly GMV as North Star, supported by buyer acquisition, seller acquisition, conversion rate, repeat purchase rate, and revenue per transaction. Guardrails might include search to purchase ratio and seller satisfaction score.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="aarrr-framework">
      <p>The AARRR framework (Pirate Metrics) organizes metrics by customer lifecycle stage. For each stage, define metrics that answer: Acquisition (How do users find us?): Visitors, signups, CAC. Activation (Do they have a great first experience?): Onboarding completion, time to value. Retention (Do they come back?): DAU/MAU, churn rate. Revenue (Do they pay?): MRR, ARPU, LTV. Referral (Do they tell others?): NPS, referral rate, K-factor.</p>

      <example type="good" title="B2B SaaS example">
        <description>North Star: Weekly Active Teams</description>
        <p>Primary KPIs: Acquisition (Marketing Qualified Leads): 200 per month. Activation (Onboarding completion at 7 days): 60%. Retention (Monthly logo retention): 95%. Revenue (Net Revenue Retention): 110%. Referral (NPS): 50 or above.</p>
        <p>Guardrails: Support tickets per user less than 0.5 per month. Page load time less than 2 seconds.</p>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Consumer app example">
        <description>North Star: Daily Active Users</description>
        <p>Primary KPIs: Acquisition (Daily app installs): 500 per day. Activation (Day 1 retention): 40%. Retention (Day 7 retention): 20%. Revenue (ARPDAU): $0.05. Referral (Organic install percentage): 30%.</p>
        <p>Guardrails: Crash rate less than 0.5%. App store rating above 4.5.</p>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Marketplace example">
        <description>North Star: Weekly GMV (Gross Merchandise Value)</description>
        <p>Primary KPIs: Acquisition Demand (New buyer signups): 1000 per week. Acquisition Supply (New seller signups): 100 per week. Activation (First purchase rate): 25%. Retention (Repeat purchase rate 30 days): 40%. Revenue (Take rate): 15%.</p>
        <p>Guardrails: Search to purchase rate above 3%. Seller satisfaction above 80%.</p>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="metric-definition-process">
      <p>Step 1: Define Business Goals. Start with strategic business goals, not metrics. Use a template: Goal (objective statement). Timeframe (when you want to achieve it). Target (quantified result). Example: Goal is to achieve product-market fit. Timeframe is 6 months. Target is 40 percent or more of users would be very disappointed without the product. These goals are your north star input. Metrics are downstream of goals.</p>

      <p>Step 2: Identify North Star Metric. A North Star metric is a single measure that best reflects the core value delivered to customers. It should lead to revenue. It must be measurable and understandable to the entire team. It must be actionable — if it drops, everyone knows what lever to pull. Characteristics: Measures core value delivered to the customer. Leads to revenue (directly or with lag). Measurable and understandable to the whole team. Actionable. Examples by product type: SaaS (Weekly active users or monthly retention rate). Marketplace (Transactions per week or weekly GMV). Media (Time spent reading or articles read per session). E-commerce (Purchases per month or monthly repeat rate).</p>

      <p>Step 3: Break Down into Primary KPIs. For each AARRR stage, define one primary metric with a target and tracking method. Limit to 3 to 5 primary KPIs total across the entire product. More than that and the team loses focus. Each primary KPI should be owned by a specific person or team.</p>

      <p>Step 4: Set Targets. Different target-setting approaches work for different situations. Baseline plus improvement: take your current metric and add a realistic percentage growth (e.g., current monthly retention 70%, target 75%). Works when you have data. Benchmark: look at industry averages for your product type. Works when you have no internal data. Goal-backward: work backward from your business goal (e.g., to hit our revenue target, we need MRR of 50k, which requires 1000 active users at 50 dollars per month). Works for strategic targets. Experimental: run a small test first to establish a baseline, then set targets. Works for new metrics. Good target criteria: Specific number (not vague). Time-bound (by when). Achievable but challenging (not too easy, not impossible). Based on data or research (not a guess).</p>

      <p>Step 5: Establish Measurement. For each metric, document everything needed to track it. Definition (exactly what counts, e.g., weekly active user means logged in at least once in the past 7 days). Data source (where data comes from, e.g., production database, analytics tool). Calculation method (the formula or query). Reporting frequency (daily, weekly, monthly). Owner (who is responsible for this metric).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <p>Too many metrics: Focus on 3-5 primary KPIs. No North Star: Define single most important metric. Vanity metrics: Test if metric drives decisions. No targets: Set quantified goals. Undefined metrics: Document exact definition. No baselines: Measure current state first. Ignoring segments: Break down by user type.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>North Star chosen for measurability rather than truth drives wrong behavior. Example: page views instead of successful task completions.</description>
        <reason>This is Goodhart's law in action: any metric that becomes a target stops being a good metric. Always define guardrails.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>AARRR is funnel-shaped, bad fit for cyclical or habit products. Consider HEART, RICE, or ICE for those.</description>
        <reason>Not all products follow the acquisition to referral funnel. Choose a framework that matches your product lifecycle.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Targets set without a baseline are theatrical. Agents will pick round numbers like 10 or 20 percent that aren't grounded.</description>
        <reason>Targets without baselines have no credibility and lead to sandbagging or gaming.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>B2B and marketplace metrics need segmentation by tier or cohort. A single MAU number hides churn.</description>
        <reason>Aggregated metrics hide crucial variation across segments and can mask real problems.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Decompose business goals into a metric tree: Goals to North Star to AARRR primary KPIs to leading indicators plus guardrails. Each node is JSON with definition, formula, source, baseline, target, owner. Run a separate agent pass to detect vanity-metric patterns and Goodhart traps. Final tree is reviewed by a human; the agent never owns the target number.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: metric-tree-builder (sonnet) decomposes goals into AARRR plus guardrails using structured output. vanity-detector (haiku) flags metrics where actionability fails the would we change behavior test. target-grounder (sonnet) pulls baselines from analytics plus benchmark data and proposes ranges, never single numbers. faion-sdd-executor-agent to lifecycle the metrics framework as a living spec.</p>

      <p>Prompt pattern for metric-tree-builder. Role: metric-tree-builder. Input: business_goals.md, product_type (saas, marketplace, consumer, or media). Output JSON with north_star containing name, definition, rationale. AARRR with acquisition, activation, retention, revenue, referral arrays. guardrails array with metric, threshold, action. Constraint: max 5 primary KPIs total. Refuse output if North Star fails actionability test.</p>

      <p>Prompt pattern for vanity-detector. Role: vanity-detector. Input: metric_tree.json. Task: for each metric, answer if value drops 50 percent what action. If none or notify only, flag as vanity.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-selection">
      <p>Filling AARRR framework template (haiku): templating, form completion. Writing metric definitions (haiku): definition synthesis from examples. Identifying primary KPIs from business goals (sonnet): goal decomposition, metric selection. Setting targets with benchmarks (sonnet): research-based reasoning, market analysis. Designing guardrail metrics and thresholds (opus): complex trade-off analysis, system optimization.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>One North Star per product line, not per team. Multiple stars create ambiguity and conflict. Teams optimize for different things and strategies diverge.</item>
        <item>Pair every primary KPI with a guardrail, for example growth (KPI) paired with churn (guardrail). Growth without retention is a leaky bucket. Revenue growth paired with customer satisfaction prevents race to the bottom.</item>
        <item>Define metrics in a semantic layer (Cube or dbt) — single source of truth defeats dashboard drift. When metrics are defined in one place, everyone references the same definition. Spreadsheet metrics diverge immediately.</item>
        <item>Set ranges, not single targets. MRR 40 to 60 thousand is more honest than a single 50 thousand and reduces sandbagging and quarter-end heroics.</item>
        <item>Review the tree quarterly; retire metrics nobody asks about — dead metrics rot dashboards and create decision fatigue.</item>
        <item>Mark each metric Input vs Output; agents naturally over-weight outputs like revenue and under-weight inputs like content production or experiment velocity.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs default to feature-style metrics like feature X usage instead of outcome metrics. Force the prompt to ask what changed for the user.</item>
        <item>Targets without baselines are hallucinated. Refuse target generation unless baseline is supplied.</item>
        <item>When asked for industry benchmark, agents fabricate plausible percentages like 15 percent activation. Require a citation URL.</item>
        <item>AARRR template completion is a haiku task; trade-off design like revenue vs retention guardrails is opus-grade.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoints: North Star choice, target ranges sign-off, guardrail thresholds.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

